'''Arthur Frederick Jones''' was an American writer and dog-show judge. In 1926 (at 20 years of age), he became an assistant editor for "Pure-Bred Dogs"(now called,"The American Kennel Gazette"), the official publication of the [[American Kennel Club]]. In 1941, he was made editor,and in 1951, managing editor. He was also Kennel Editor of the ''[[New York Times]]'', and was chosen as special editor of dog terms for ''[[Webster's New International Dictionary]]''. He supplied much of the information for the K-9 manuals used by the [[U.S. Army]] in [[World War II]]. He served eight times as master of ceremonies for the [[National Dog Show]]. In 1956, Arthur Frederick Jones was the winner of the Kiblon Memorial Award (the top award in dog-writing,sponsored by the [[Dog Writers Association of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://purebreddogwriters.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/Jones-pdf2.pdf|title=Red Barber of the Dog|last=Mahood|first=Jan|date=June 5, 2008|work=AKC Gazette|pages=38–41|accessdate=2 October 2012}}</ref>

