{{Infobox person | name = Lennon Parham | image = Lennonparham.jpg | imagesize = | caption = Parham in 2009 | birth_name = Maria Lennon Parham | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1976|10|26}} | birth_place = [[Marietta, Georgia|Marietta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S. | occupation = Actress, comedian, writer | years_active = 2001–present | spouse = Javier Guzman (2006–present) | children = 2 }}
'''Maria Lennon Parham''' (born October 26, 1976) is an [[United States|American]] actress and improvisational comedian from the [[Upright Citizens Brigade Theatre]]. With frequent collaborator [[Jessica St. Clair]], she created and co-starred in [[NBC]]'s ''[[Best Friends Forever (TV series)|Best Friends Forever]]'' and [[USA Network]]'s ''[[Playing House (TV series)|Playing House]]''. She also co-starred in the [[CBS]] sitcom ''[[Accidentally on Purpose (TV series)|Accidentally on Purpose]]'' from 2009 to 2010.
==Early life== Parham was born in [[Marietta, Georgia|Marietta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. She attended [[Parkview High School (Georgia)|Parkview High School]] in Lilburn, Georgia, and graduated with a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S. Degree]] in [[Theatre studies|Theatre]] from the [[University of Evansville]]. Following college, she taught [[French language|French]] for two years at T. L. Weston High School in [[Greenville, Mississippi|Greenville]], [[Mississippi]], as part of the [[Teach For America]] program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://losangeles.ucbtheatre.com/talent/view/617|title=UCB Theater • Lennon Parham|publisher=Upright Citizens Brigade |date= |accessdate=2014-03-23}}</ref>
==Career== After her stint as a French teacher, Parham began performing comedy with the Upright Citizens Brigade Theatre. During this time, she starred in the two-person show, ''The Adventures of Lock & Kay'', and the one-woman show, ''She Tried to be Normal''. In the fall of 2009, Parham began a supporting role in the comedy ''[[Accidentally on Purpose (TV series)|Accidentally on Purpose]]''.
Parham and frequent collaborator [[Jessica St. Clair]] created and starred in the [[NBC]] comedy ''[[Best Friends Forever (TV series)|Best Friends Forever]]'', which ran for one season in 2012. Their second sitcom, ''[[Playing House (TV series)|Playing House]]'', premiered on [[USA Network|USA]] on April 29, 2014 and lasted three seasons. In 2015, Parham and St. Clair spun-off their ''[[Comedy Bang! Bang!]]'' characters Wompler and Listler for a new [[Earwolf]] podcast called ''[[Womp It Up!|WOMP It Up!]]'', with St. Clair as host Marissa Wompler and Parham co-hosting as Marissa's teacher Charlotte Listler. Frequent guests on the podcast include [[Brian Huskey]] as Marissa's stepdad "Seth" and [[Jason Mantzoukas]] as Marissa's former flame Eric "Gutterballs" Gutterman.
Parham has made appearances on television programs such as ''[[Veep (TV series)|Veep]]'', ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'', ''[[Comedy Bang! Bang! (TV series)|Comedy Bang! Bang!]]'', ''[[Bad Judge]]'', ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'', ''[[Review (TV series)|Review]]'' and ''[[Mad Men]]''. Her notable work in film includes ''[[Confessions of a Shopaholic (film)|Confessions of a Shopaholic]]'', ''[[Splinterheads]]'', and ''[[Horrible Bosses 2]]''.
==Personal life== Parham is married to Javier Guzman. Their daughter Saraya was born on April 21, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2013/05/31/lennon-parham-welcomes-daughter-saraya-jessica-st-clair-pregnant/ |title=Jessica St. Clair and Lennon Parham Bond Over Baby Girls – Moms & Babies – Moms & Babies - People.com |publisher=Celebritybabies.people.com |date= |accessdate=2013-07-17}}</ref> Their second child was born in October 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/lennonparham/status/803337008714104832|title=Lennon Parham on Twitter|last=|first=|date=November 28, 2016|website=Twitter|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=September 6, 2017}}</ref>
In 2015, Jessica St. Clair said she and Parham had learned [[Transcendental Meditation technique|Transcendental Meditation]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Corridan |first1=Kara |title=A Convo with Two Really Cool Moms |url=http://www.parents.com/parents-magazine/parents-perspective/a-convo-with-two-really-cool-moms/ |website=Parents |accessdate=18 September 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bddWQKys?url=http://www.parents.com/parents-magazine/parents-perspective/a-convo-with-two-really-cool-moms/ |archivedate=18 September 2015 |date=2015 |quote=Lennon’s husband worked at a school where they taught transcendental meditation and took time out of the school day to meditate. Seeing the change in the students' lives, we thought it would be useful to us as well. So Lennon and I learned meditation from a phenomenal teacher, Lynn Kaplan, through the David Lynch Foundation, and we try and meditate at least once a day. |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
