{{Infobox Officeholder | honorific-prefix = | name =Mahmud Kanti Bello | honorific-suffix = | image = | imagesize = | smallimage = | caption = | order = | office =National Senator | term_start =2003 | term_end =2011 | predecessor =Abdu Yandoma | successor =Hadi Sirika | constituency =Katsina North | majority = | birth_date ={{birth date|1945|1|14}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{death date and age|2017|8|29|1945|1|14}} | death_place = Abuja | nationality =[[Nigeria]] | party =[[Congress for Progressive Change]] (CPC) | spouse = | relations = | children = | residence = | alma_mater = | occupation = | profession =Politician | religion =Islam | signature = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Mahmud Kanti Bello''' (14 January 1945 – 29 August 2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunnewsonline.com/kanti-bello-family-silent-on-cause-of-death/|title=Kanti Bello: Family silent on cause of death {{!}} The Sun News|website=sunnewsonline.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-12-20}}</ref> was a [[Nigeria]]n senator who represented the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] in the Katsina North Senatorial District of [[Katsina State]], and was the Senate majority whip. He became a senator in 2003 and was reelected in 2007. Bello died in the early hours of 29 August 2017 in Abuja. He was 72. He represented Daura Senatorial Zone between 2003 and 2007 and again from 2007 to 2011 and was the pioneer Managing Director of Katsina Steel Rolling Mill.<ref name=nassnig>{{cite web|url=http://www.nassnig.org/senate/member.php?senator=80 |title=Sen. Mahmud Kanti Bello |publisher=National Assembly of Nigeria |accessdate=2009-09-15 |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080607060020/http://www.nassnig.org/senate/member.php?senator=80 |archivedate=June 7, 2008 }}</ref>
==Background== Mahmud Kanti Bello was born on 14 January 1945, and is of [[Hausa people|Hausa]] origin. He received a Bachelor of Engineering degree from [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]], [[Kaduna State]] in Northern Nigeria.<ref name=nassnig/>
==Career== [[image:NigeriaKatsina.png|thumb|right|200px|[[Katsina State]] in [[Nigeria]]]] Mahmud Kanti Bello was elected as a [[Katsina]] senator in 2003 on the [[All Nigeria Peoples Party]] (ANPP) platform. In the 2004 local elections in his state, he protested strongly against electoral fraud which resulted in [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|People's Democratic Party]] (PDP) candidates being returned. However, in 2007 he successfully ran for reelection on a PDP slate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nigeriavillagesquare.com/articles/guest-articles/enter-senator-kanti-bellos-shop/pdf.html |title=Enter Senator Kanti Bello's Shop! |publisher=Nigerian Village Square |date=15 January 2007 |accessdate=2009-09-15}}</ref> By the middle of his second term in the senate, Bello was among those senators who had not solely sponsored any private bills.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sunday.dailytrust.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=640:why-are-they-in-the-senate&catid=57:cover&Itemid=126 |publisher=Sunday Daily Trust |title=Why are they in the Senate? |date=12 July 2009 |accessdate=2009-09-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708221443/http://sunday.dailytrust.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=640%3Awhy-are-they-in-the-senate&catid=57%3Acover&Itemid=126 |archivedate=8 July 2011 |df= }}</ref>
In a statement in January 2009, Bello lashed out against governors who withhold local government funds, releasing them only at their convenience, including the governor of his state, [[Ibrahim Shema]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200901300459.html |title=LG Funds - Senator Accuses Govs of Criminality |date=30 January 2009 |publisher=Leadership |accessdate=2009-09-15}}</ref> In discussion over the proposed bill to control desertification, Senator Bello strongly opposed Senator [[Grace Folashade Bent]], chair of the Senate Committee on Environment and Ecology, who wanted to include other environmental issues in the bill.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200902190403.html |title=Senate Set to Establish Desertification Control Commission |date=19 February 2009 |publisher=Daily Trust |accessdate=2009-09-15}}</ref>
In July 2009, South-South senators initiated a motion to demand dismissal of Minister of Petroleum, [[Rilwan Lukman]], and [[Mohammed Barkindo]] of the [[Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation]], on the basis of alleged anti-Niger Delta policies. Senator Bello opposed the motion on a point of order, without success.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://odili.net/news/source/2009/jul/31/607.html |title=Sack Lukman, Barkindo now - Senate orders Yar’Adua |date=July 31, 2009 |publisher=Nigerian Tribune |accessdate=2009-09-15}}{{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In 2009, Bello was the Nigerian Amir-Hajj for the Nigerian pilgrims to Saudi Arabia. He broke a record where for the first time in over 20 years all the pilgrims left on time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2017/08/sen-mahmud-kanti-bello-buried-katsina/|title=Sen. Mahmud Kanti-Bello to be buried in Katsina - Vanguard News|date=2017-08-29|work=Vanguard News|access-date=2018-10-15|language=en-US}}</ref>
