'''Étienne Maurice Gérard, 1er [[Count|Comte]] Gérard''' (4 April 1773{{spaced ndash}}17 April 1852) was a French general, statesman and [[Marshal of France]]. He served under a succession of French governments including the ''ancien regime'' monarchy, the Revolutionary governments, the Restorations, the [[July Monarchy]], the [[First French Republic|First]] and [[Second French Republic|Second Republics]], and the [[First French Empire|First Empire]] (and arguably the [[Second French Empire|Second]]),{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}} becoming Prime Minister briefly in 1834.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}

==Biography==
===Early life and career===
Born at [[Damvilliers]], in [[Lorraine (province)|Lorraine]], he joined a [[French Revolutionary Army|battalion of volunteers]] in 1791, and served in the [[Campaigns of 1792 in the French Revolutionary Wars|campaigns of 1792–1793]] under Generals [[Charles François Dumouriez]] and [[Jean-Baptiste Jourdan]]. In 1795, he served [[Charles XIV John of Sweden|Jean-Baptiste Bernadotte]] as [[aide-de-camp]]. In 1799 he was promoted ''[[Squadron (army)|chef d'escadron]]'', and in 1800 [[colonel]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}}

===Rise to prominence===
He distinguished himself at the battles of [[battle of Austerlitz|Austerlitz]] and [[battle of Jena|Jena]], and was made [[Brigadier General]] in November 1806, and for his conduct in the [[battle of Wagram]] he was created a [[baron]] of the [[First French Empire]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}}

In the [[Peninsular War|Spanish campaign of 1810 and 1811]], Gérard gained special distinction at the [[battle of Fuentes de Onoro]]; and in the [[Napoleon's invasion of Russia|expedition to Russia]] he was present at the [[Battle of Smolensk (1812)|battle of Smolensk]] and the [[battle of Valutino]], and displayed such bravery and ability in the [[battle of Borodino]] that he was made ''[[Général|général de division]]''. He won further distinction in the disastrous retreat from Moscow.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}}

===Campaigns of 1813–1814===
In the [[War of the Sixth Coalition|campaign of 1813]], in command of a [[Division (military)|division]], he took part in the [[battle of Lützen (1813)|battle of Lützen]] and the [[battle of Bautzen]], as well as in the operations of [[Étienne-Jacques-Joseph-Alexandre MacDonald|Marshal Macdonald]], and at the [[battle of Leipzig]] (in which he commanded the XI Corps) he was gravely wounded. After the battle of Bautzen, he was created by [[Napoleon I of France|Napoleon]] a [[count]] of the Empire.
In the [[Six Days Campaign]] of 1814, and especially at [[Battle of La Rothière|La Rothière]] and the [[battle of Montereau]], he won still greater distinction.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}}

===Restoration and July Revolution===
After the first [[Bourbon Restoration]], he was named by [[List of French monarchs|King]] [[Louis XVIII of France|Louis XVIII]] Grand Cross of the [[Legion of Honor]] and [[Order of Saint Louis|chevalier of St Louis]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}}

During the [[Hundred Days]], Napoleon made Gérard a [[Peerage of France|Peer of France]] and placed him in command of the IV Corps of the Army of the North. In this capacity Gérard took a brilliant part in the [[battle of Ligny]], and on the morning of 18 June he was foremost in advising [[Emmanuel, marquis de Grouchy|Marshal Grouchy]] to march to the sound of the guns to aid the emperor at [[battle of Waterloo|Waterloo]]. Having failed in this he took part in the [[battle of Wavre]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}}

Gérard retired to [[Brussels]] after the fall of Napoleon, and did not return to France until 1817. He sat as a member of the Restoration's [[Chamber of Deputies of France|Chamber of Deputies]] in 1822–1824, and was re-elected in 1827.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}}

Gérard took part in the [[July Revolution]] of 1830, after which he was appointed minister of war and named a [[Marshal of France]]. On account of his health he resigned the office of [[List of Defense Ministers of France|War Minister]] in the following October.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}}

===Belgian campaign and later distinctions===
However, in 1831 he took the command of the Northern Army, and was successful in forcing the army of the [[United Kingdom of the Netherlands|Netherlands]] to withdraw from [[Belgium]] (''see [[Belgian Revolution]]''). In 1832 he commanded the besieging army in the famous [[Siege of Antwerp (1832)|scientific siege]] of the citadel of [[Antwerp]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}}

He was again chosen war minister in July 1834,{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}} and served as [[List of Prime Ministers of France|Prime Minister]] of the [[July Monarchy]],<ref name="napoleon.org">[http://www.napoleon.org/fr/salle_lecture/biographies/files/Gerard_Maurice.asp «GERARD, MAURICE-ETIENNE (1773-1852), GÉNÉRAL, MARÉCHAL»], from the website napoleon.org</ref> but resigned in the following October. In 1836 he was named grand chancellor of the Legion of Honour in succession to [[Édouard Adolphe Casimir Joseph Mortier|Marshal Mortier]], and in 1838 commander of the National Guards of the [[Seine (département)|Seine]] ''[[département]]'', an office which he held until 1842. He became a [[Senate of France|senator]] of the [[Second French Empire|Second Empire]] in 1852 (before it was formally instituted), and died in the same year, aged 79.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=764}}

==Marriage and descendants==
Gérard married Rosemonde de Valence. Their granddaughter was [[Rosemonde Gérard]].<ref name="napoleon.org"/>

